To configure real-time collaborative editing in Snipara, you would typically follow these steps:

1. **Set Up the Environment**: Ensure that your Snipara environment is properly set up and that you have access to the necessary APIs and services.

2. **Use the MCP Server**: The Snipara Model Context Protocol (MCP) server supports real-time collaborative features. You will need to integrate the MCP server into your application.

3. **Implement WebSocket or SSE**: For real-time collaboration, you can use WebSockets or Server-Sent Events (SSE) to enable live updates. Snipara provides an SSE transport endpoint that you can utilize.

   Example configuration for SSE:
   ```json
   {
     "mcpServers": [
       {
         "name": "rlm",
         "transport": {
           "type": "sse",
           "url": "https://api.rlmsaas.com/v1/PROJECT_ID/mcp/sse",
           "headers": {
             "X-API-Key": "{{RLM_API_KEY}}"
           }
         }
       }
     ]
   }
   ```

4. **Handle Document Changes**: Implement logic in your application to listen for changes made by other users. When a user makes an edit, broadcast that change to all connected clients.

5. **Merge Changes**: Ensure that your application can handle merging changes from multiple users. This may involve conflict resolution strategies to manage simultaneous edits.

6. **Testing**: Thoroughly test the collaborative editing feature to ensure that it works seamlessly across different users and devices.

7. **Documentation**: Refer to the Snipara documentation for any specific APIs or methods that may assist in implementing collaborative features.

